[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] In mathematics, a **functional equation** is, in the broadest meaning, an equation in which one or several functions appear as unknowns.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] So, differential equations and integral equations are functional equations.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] However, a more restricted meaning is often used, where a *functional equation* is an equation that relates several values of the same function.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] For example, the logarithm functions are essentially characterized by the *logarithmic functional equation* ŌüĀ $\log(xy)=\log(x)+\log(y)$ ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] If the domain of the unknown function is supposed to be the natural numbers, the function is generally viewed as a sequence, and, in this case, a functional equation (in the narrower meaning) is called a recurrence relation.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] Thus the term *functional equation* is used mainly for real functions and complex functions.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] Moreover a smoothness condition is often assumed for the solutions, since without such a condition, most functional equations have highly irregular solutions.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] One feature that all of the examples listed above have in common is that, in each case, two or more known functions (sometimes multiplication by a constant, sometimes addition of two variables, sometimes the identity function) are inside the argument of the unknown functions to be solved for.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] The BohrŌĆōMollerup theorem is another well-known example.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] The involutions are characterized by the functional equation $f(f(x))=x$ .
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] which includes the previous three as special cases or limits.
[src:functional-equations/functional-equation] In dynamic programming a variety of successive approximation methods are used to solve Bellman's functional equation, including methods based on fixed point iterations.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] In mathematics, the **gamma function** (represented by ŌüĀ $\Gamma$ ŌüĀ, capital Greek letter gamma) is the most common extension of the factorial function to complex numbers.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] First studied by Daniel Bernoulli, the gamma function $\Gamma (z)$ is defined for all complex numbers z except non-positive integers, and $\Gamma (n)=(n-1)!$ for every positive integer ŌüĀ n ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Since the gamma function has no zeros, its reciprocal ${\frac {1}{\Gamma }}$ is an entire function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Other extensions of the factorial function do exist, but the gamma function is the most popular and useful.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] It appears as a factor in various probability-distribution functions and other formulas in the fields of probability, statistics, analytic number theory, and combinatorics.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function can be seen as a solution to the interpolation problem of finding a smooth curve $y=f(x)$ that connects the points of the factorial sequence: $(x,y)=(n,n!)$ for all positive integer values of ŌüĀ n ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The simple formula for the factorial, $x!=1\cdot 2\cdot 3\cdots x$ is only valid when x is a positive integer, and no elementary function has this property, but a good solution is the gamma function ŌüĀ $f(x)=\Gamma (x+1)$ ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function is not only smooth but analytic (except at the non-positive integers), and it can be defined in several explicit ways.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] However, it is not the only analytic function that extends the factorial, as one may add any analytic function that is zero on the positive integers, such as $k\sin(m\pi x)$ for an integer ŌüĀ m ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Such a function is known as a pseudogamma function, the most famous being the Hadamard function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] But this still does not give a unique solution, since it allows for multiplication by any periodic function $g(x)$ with $g(x)=g(x+1)$ and ŌüĀ $g(0)=1$ ŌüĀ, such as ŌüĀ $g(x)=e^{k\sin(m\pi x)}$ ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] One way to resolve the ambiguity is the BohrŌĆōMollerup theorem, which shows that $f(x)=\Gamma (x)$ is the unique interpolating function for the factorial, defined over the positive reals, which is logarithmically convex, meaning that $y=\log f(x)$ is convex.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The notation $\Gamma (z)$ is due to Legendre.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] If the real part of the complex number z is strictly positive (ŌüĀ $\Re (z)>0$ ŌüĀ), then the integral $\Gamma (z)=\int _{0}^{\infty }t^{z-1}e^{-t}\,dt$ converges absolutely, and is known as the **Euler integral of the second kind**.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Thus we have shown that $\Gamma (n)=(n-1)!$ for any positive integer n by induction.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The identity ${\textstyle z\Gamma (z)=\Gamma (z+1)}$ can be used (or, yielding the same result, analytic continuation can be used) to uniquely extend the integral formulation for $\Gamma (z)$ to a meromorphic function defined for all complex numbers ŌüĀ z ŌüĀ, except integers less than or equal to zero.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] It is this extended version that is commonly referred to as the gamma function.
