[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] An alternative notation introduced by Gauss is the $\Pi$ -function, a shifted version of the gamma function: $\Pi (z)=\Gamma (z+1)=z\Gamma (z)=\int _{0}^{\infty }e^{-t}t^{z}\,dt,$ so that $\Pi (n)=n!$ for every non-negative integer ŌüĀ n ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The shifted reciprocal gamma function is sometimes denoted ŌüĀ $\pi (z)={\frac {1}{\Pi (z)}}$ ŌüĀ, an entire function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The values presented here are truncated rather than rounded.) The complex-valued gamma function is undefined for non-positive integers, but in these cases the value can be defined in the Riemann sphere as ŌüĀ $\infty$ ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Because the gamma and factorial functions grow so rapidly for moderately large arguments, many computing environments include a function that returns the natural logarithm of the gamma function, often given the name `lgamma` or `lngamma` in programming environments or `gammaln` in spreadsheets.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] This grows much more slowly, and for combinatorial calculations allows adding and subtracting logarithmic values instead of multiplying and dividing very large values.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The digamma function, which is the derivative of this function, is also commonly seen.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] is often used since it allows one to determine function values in one strip of width 1 in z from the neighbouring strip.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] In particular, starting with a good approximation for a z with large real part one may go step by step down to the desired ŌüĀ z ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The coefficients of the terms with $k>1$ of $z^{1-k}$ in the last expansion are simply ${\frac {B_{k}}{k(k-1)}},$ where the $B_{k}$ are the Bernoulli numbers.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The BohrŌĆōMollerup theorem states that among all functions extending the factorial functions to the positive real numbers, only the gamma function is log-convex, that is, its natural logarithm is convex on the positive real axis.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Another characterisation is given by the Wielandt theorem.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] In a certain sense, the log-gamma function is the more natural form; it makes some intrinsic attributes of the function clearer.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] A striking example is the Taylor series of log╬ō around 1: $\operatorname {log\Gamma } (z+1)=-\gamma z+\sum _{k=2}^{\infty }{\frac {\zeta (k)}{k}}\,(-z)^{k}\qquad \forall \;|z|<1$ with ŌüĀ $\zeta (k)$ ŌüĀ denoting the Riemann zeta function at ŌüĀ k ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] There also exist special formulas for the logarithm of the gamma function for rational ŌüĀ z ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] When $z=1$ it follows that $\int _{0}^{1}\operatorname {log\Gamma } (x)\,dx={\frac {1}{2}}\log(2\pi ),$ and this is a consequence of Raabe's formula as well.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Bailey and his co-authors gave an evaluation for $L_{n}:=\int _{0}^{1}\log ^{n}\Gamma (x)\,dx$ when $n=1,2$ in terms of the TornheimŌĆōWitten zeta function and its derivatives.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function can be computed to fixed precision for $\Re (z)\in [1,2]$ by applying integration by parts to Euler's integral.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] When ŌüĀ $\Re (z)\in [1,2]$ ŌüĀ and ŌüĀ $x\geq 1$ ŌüĀ, the absolute value of the last integral is smaller than ŌüĀ $(x+1)e^{-x}$ ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] By choosing a large enough ŌüĀ x ŌüĀ, this last expression can be made smaller than $2^{-N}$ for any desired value ŌüĀ N ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Thus, the gamma function can be evaluated to N bits of precision with the above series.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] A fast algorithm for calculation of the Euler gamma function for any algebraic argument (including rational) was constructed by E.A.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] For arguments that are integer multiples of ŌüĀ ${\tfrac {1}{24}}$ ŌüĀ, the gamma function can also be evaluated quickly using arithmeticŌĆōgeometric mean iterations (see particular values of the gamma function).
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Unlike many other functions, such as a normal distribution, no obvious fast, accurate implementation that is easy to implement for the gamma function $\Gamma (z)$ is easily found.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Therefore, it is worth investigating potential solutions.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] For the case that speed is more important than accuracy, published tables for $\Gamma (z)$ are easily found in an Internet search, such as the Online Wiley Library.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Such tables may be used with linear interpolation.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] Greater accuracy is obtainable with the use of cubic interpolation at the cost of more computational overhead.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] If interpolation tables are not desirable, then the Lanczos approximation mentioned above works well for 1 to 2 digits of accuracy for small, commonly used values of ŌüĀ z ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p01] If the Lanczos approximation is not sufficiently accurate, the Stirling's formula for the Gamma Function may be used.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] One author describes the gamma function as "Arguably, the most common special function, or the least 'special' of them.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The other transcendental functions [...] are called 'special' because you could conceivably avoid some of them by staying away from many specialized mathematical topics.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function finds application in such diverse areas as quantum physics, astrophysics and fluid dynamics.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The gamma distribution, which is formulated in terms of the gamma function, is used in statistics to model a wide range of processes; for example, the time between occurrences of earthquakes.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The primary reason for the gamma function's usefulness in such contexts is the prevalence of expressions of the type ŌüĀ $f(t)e^{-g(t)}$ ŌüĀ, which describe processes that decay exponentially in time or space.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Integrals of such expressions can occasionally be solved in terms of the gamma function when no elementary solution exists.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The fact that the integration is performed along the entire positive real line might signify that the gamma function describes the cumulation of a time-dependent process that continues indefinitely, or the value might be the total of a distribution in an infinite space.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] It is of course frequently useful to take limits of integration other than 0 and $\infty$ to describe the cumulation of a finite process, in which case the ordinary gamma function is no longer a solution; the solution is then called an incomplete gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] An important category of exponentially decaying functions is that of Gaussian functions $ae^{-{\frac {(x-b)^{2}}{c^{2}}}}$ and integrals thereof, such as the error function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] There are many interrelations between these functions and the gamma function; notably, the factor ${\sqrt {\pi }}$ obtained by evaluating ${\textstyle \Gamma \left({\frac {1}{2}}\right)}$ is the "same" as that found in the normalizing factor of the error function and the normal distribution.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The integrals discussed so far involve transcendental functions, but the gamma function also arises from integrals of purely algebraic functions.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] In particular, the arc lengths of ellipses and of the lemniscate, which are curves defined by algebraic equations, are given by elliptic integrals that in special cases can be evaluated in terms of the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function can also be used to calculate "volume" and "area" of n -dimensional hyperspheres.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function's ability to generalize factorial products immediately leads to applications in many areas of mathematics; in combinatorics, and by extension in areas such as probability theory and the calculation of power series.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Many expressions involving products of successive integers can be written as some combination of factorials, the most important example perhaps being that of the binomial coefficient.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The example of binomial coefficients motivates why the properties of the gamma function when extended to negative numbers are natural.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] A binomial coefficient gives the number of ways to choose k elements from a set of n elements; if ŌüĀ $k>n$ ŌüĀ, there are of course no ways.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] If ŌüĀ $k>n$ ŌüĀ, then $(n-k)!$ is the factorial of a negative integer and hence infinite if we use the gamma function definition of factorialsŌĆödividing by infinity gives the expected value of ŌüĀ 0 ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] We can replace the factorial by a gamma function to extend any such formula to the complex numbers.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Generally, this works for any product wherein each factor is a rational function of the index variable, by factoring the rational function into linear expressions.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] If we have a way to calculate the gamma function numerically, it is very simple to calculate numerical values of such products.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The number of gamma functions in the right-hand side depends only on the degree of the polynomials, so it does not matter whether $b-a$ equals 5 or 105.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] By taking the appropriate limits, the equation can also be made to hold even when the left-hand product contains zeros or poles.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] By taking limits, certain rational products with infinitely many factors can be evaluated in terms of the gamma function as well.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Due to the Weierstrass factorization theorem, analytic functions can be written as infinite products, and these can sometimes be represented as finite products or quotients of the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] We have already seen one striking example: the reflection formula essentially represents the sine function as the product of two gamma functions.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Starting from this formula, the exponential function as well as all the trigonometric and hyperbolic functions can be expressed in terms of the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] More functions yet, including the hypergeometric function and special cases thereof, can be represented by means of complex contour integrals of products and quotients of the gamma function, called MellinŌĆōBarnes integrals.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] An application of the gamma function is the study of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Among other things, this provides an explicit form for the analytic continuation of the zeta function to a meromorphic function in the complex plane and leads to an immediate proof that the zeta function has infinitely many so-called "trivial" zeros on the real line.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function has caught the interest of some of the most prominent mathematicians of all time.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Its history, notably documented by Philip J.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Davis in an article that won him the 1963 Chauvenet Prize, reflects many of the major developments within mathematics since the 18th century.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] In the words of Davis, "each generation has found something of interest to say about the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The problem of extending the factorial to non-integer arguments was apparently first considered by Daniel Bernoulli and Christian Goldbach in the 1720s.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] In particular, in a letter from Bernoulli to Goldbach dated 6 October 1729 Bernoulli introduced the product representation $x!=\lim _{n\to \infty }\left(n+1+{\frac {x}{2}}\right)^{x-1}\prod _{k=1}^{n}{\frac {k+1}{k+x}},$ which is well defined for real values of x other than the negative integers.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] He wrote to Goldbach again on 8 January 1730, to announce his discovery of the integral representation $n!=\int _{0}^{1}(-\log s)^{n}\,ds,$ which is valid when the real part of the complex number ŌüĀ n ŌüĀ is strictly greater than $-1$ (i.e., ŌüĀ $\Re (n)>-1$ ŌüĀ).
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] By the change of variables ŌüĀ $t=-\ln s$ ŌüĀ, this becomes the familiar Euler integral.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Euler published his results in the paper "De progressionibus transcendentibus seu quarum termini generales algebraice dari nequeunt" ("On transcendental progressions, that is, those whose general terms cannot be given algebraically"), submitted to the St.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Euler further discovered some of the gamma function's important functional properties, including the reflection formula.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] James Stirling, a contemporary of Euler, also attempted to find a continuous expression for the factorial and came up with what is now known as Stirling's formula.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Although Stirling's formula gives a good estimate of ŌüĀ $n!$ ŌüĀ, also for non-integers, it does not provide the exact value.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Extensions of his formula that correct the error were given by Stirling himself and by Jacques Philippe Marie Binet.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Carl Friedrich Gauss rewrote Euler's product as $\Gamma (z)=\lim _{m\to \infty }{\frac {m^{z}m!}{z(z+1)(z+2)\cdots (z+m)}}$ and used this formula to discover new properties of the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Although Euler was a pioneer in the theory of complex variables, he does not appear to have considered the factorial of a complex number, as instead Gauss first did.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Gauss also proved the multiplication theorem of the gamma function and investigated the connection between the gamma function and elliptic integrals.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Karl Weierstrass further established the role of the gamma function in complex analysis, starting from yet another product representation, $\Gamma (z)={\frac {e^{-\gamma z}}{z}}\prod _{k=1}^{\infty }\left(1+{\frac {z}{k}}\right)^{-1}e^{\frac {z}{k}},$ where $\gamma$ is the EulerŌĆōMascheroni constant.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Weierstrass originally wrote his product as one for ŌüĀ $\textstyle {\frac {1}{\Gamma }}$ ŌüĀ, in which case it is taken over the function's zeros rather than its poles.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Inspired by this result, he proved what is known as the Weierstrass factorization theoremŌĆöthat any entire function can be written as a product over its zeros in the complex plane; a generalization of the fundamental theorem of algebra.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The name gamma function and the symbol $\Gamma$ were introduced by Adrien-Marie Legendre around 1811; Legendre also rewrote Euler's integral definition in its modern form.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Although the symbol is an upper-case Greek gamma, there is no accepted standard for whether the function name should be written "gamma function" or "Gamma function" (some authors simply write "ŌüĀ $\Gamma$ ŌüĀ-function").
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The alternative "pi function" notation $\Pi (z)=z!$ due to Gauss is sometimes encountered in older literature, but Legendre's notation is dominant in modern works.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] It is justified to ask why we distinguish between the "ordinary factorial" and the gamma function by using distinct symbols, and particularly why the gamma function should be normalized to $\Gamma (n+1)=n!$ instead of simply using ŌüĀ $\Gamma (n)=n!$ ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Consider that the notation for exponents, ŌüĀ $x^{n}$ ŌüĀ, has been generalized from integers to complex numbers $x^{z}$ without any change.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Legendre's motivation for the normalization is not known, and has been criticized as cumbersome by some (the 20th-century mathematician Cornelius Lanczos, for example, called it "void of any rationality" and would instead use ŌüĀ $z!$ ŌüĀ).
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Legendre's normalization does simplify some formulae, but complicates others.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] From a modern point of view, the Legendre normalization of the gamma function is the integral of the additive character $e^{-x}$ against the multiplicative character $x^{z}$ with respect to the Haar measure ${\textstyle {\frac {dx}{x}}}$ on the Lie group ŌüĀ $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ ŌüĀ.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Thus this normalization makes it clearer that the gamma function is a continuous analogue of a Gauss sum.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] It is somewhat problematic that a large number of definitions have been given for the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Although they describe the same function, it is not entirely straightforward to prove the equivalence.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Stirling never proved that his extended formula corresponds exactly to Euler's gamma function; a proof was first given by Charles Hermite in 1900.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Instead of finding a specialized proof for each formula, it would be desirable to have a general method of identifying the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] One way to prove equivalence would be to find a differential equation that characterizes the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Most special functions in applied mathematics arise as solutions to differential equations, whose solutions are unique.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] However, the gamma function does not appear to satisfy any simple differential equation.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Otto H├Člder proved in 1887 that the gamma function at least does not satisfy any *algebraic* differential equation by showing that a solution to such an equation could not satisfy the gamma function's recurrence formula, making it a transcendentally transcendental function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] This result is known as H├Člder's theorem.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] A definite and generally applicable characterization of the gamma function was not given until 1922.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The BohrŌĆōMollerup theorem is useful because it is relatively easy to prove logarithmic convexity for any of the different formulas used to define the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Taking things further, instead of defining the gamma function by any particular formula, we can choose the conditions of the BohrŌĆōMollerup theorem as the definition, and then pick any formula we like that satisfies the conditions as a starting point for studying the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] This approach was used by the Bourbaki group.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Borwein & Corless review three centuries of work on the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Although the gamma function can be calculated virtually as easily as any mathematically simpler function with a modern computerŌĆöeven with a programmable pocket calculatorŌĆöthis was of course not always the case.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Until the mid-20th century, mathematicians relied on hand-made tables; in the case of the gamma function, notably a table computed by Gauss in 1813 and one computed by Legendre in 1825.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Tables of complex values of the gamma function, as well as hand-drawn graphs, were given in *Tables of Functions With Formulas and Curves* by Jahnke and Emde, first published in Germany in 1909.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] There was in fact little practical need for anything but real values of the gamma function until the 1930s, when applications for the complex gamma function were discovered in theoretical physics.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] As electronic computers became available for the production of tables in the 1950s, several extensive tables for the complex gamma function were published to meet the demand, including a table accurate to 12 decimal places from the U.S.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Double-precision floating-point implementations of the gamma function and its logarithm are now available in most scientific computing software and special functions libraries, for example TK Solver, Matlab, GNU Octave, and the GNU Scientific Library.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function was also added to the C standard library (math.h).
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] Arbitrary-precision implementations are available in most computer algebra systems, such as Mathematica and Maple.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] PARI/GP, MPFR and MPFUN contain free arbitrary-precision implementations.
[src:functional-equations/gamma-function-p02] In some software calculators, such the Windows Calculator and GNOME Calculator, the factorial function returns $\Gamma (x+1)$ when the input x is a non-integer value.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] In mathematics, a **generating function** is a representation of an infinite sequence of numbers as the coefficients of a formal power series.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Generating functions are often expressed in closed form (rather than as a series), by some expression involving operations on the formal series.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] There are various types of generating functions, including **ordinary generating functions**, **exponential generating functions**, *Lambert series*, *Bell series*, and *Dirichlet series*.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Every sequence in principle has a generating function of each type (except that Lambert and Dirichlet series require indices to start at 1 rather than 0), but the ease with which they can be handled may differ considerably.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The particular generating function, if any, that is most useful in a given context will depend upon the nature of the sequence and the details of the problem being addressed.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Generating functions are sometimes called **generating series**, in that a series of terms can be said to be the generator of its sequence of term coefficients.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Generating functions were first introduced by Abraham de Moivre in 1730, in order to solve the general linear recurrence problem.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Unlike an ordinary series, the *formal* power series is not required to converge: in fact, the generating function is not actually regarded as a function, and the "variable" remains an indeterminate.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] One can generalize to formal power series in more than one indeterminate, to encode information about infinite multi-dimensional arrays of numbers.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Thus generating functions are not functions in the formal sense of a mapping from a domain to a codomain.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] These expressions in terms of the indeterminate x may involve arithmetic operations, differentiation with respect to x and composition with (i.e., substitution into) other generating functions; since these operations are also defined for functions, the result looks like a function of x.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Indeed, the closed form expression can often be interpreted as a function that can be evaluated at (sufficiently small) concrete values of x, and which has the formal series as its series expansion; this explains the designation "generating functions".
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] However such interpretation is not required to be possible, because formal series are not required to give a convergent series when a nonzero numeric value is substituted for x.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Not all expressions that are meaningful as functions of x are meaningful as expressions designating formal series; for example, negative and fractional powers of x are examples of functions that do not have a corresponding formal power series.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] When the term *generating function* is used without qualification, it is usually taken to mean an ordinary generating function.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The *ordinary generating function* of a sequence *a**n* is: $G(a_{n};x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}x^{n}.$ If *a**n* is the probability mass function of a discrete random variable, then its ordinary generating function is called a probability-generating function.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Exponential generating functions are generally more convenient than ordinary generating functions for combinatorial enumeration problems that involve labelled objects.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Another benefit of exponential generating functions is that they are useful in transferring linear recurrence relations to the realm of differential equations.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] For example, take the Fibonacci sequence {*fn*} that satisfies the linear recurrence relation *f**n*+2 = *f**n*+1 + *f**n*.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] and its derivatives can readily be shown to satisfy the differential equation EFŌĆ│(*x*) = EFŌĆ▓(*x*) + EF(*x*) as a direct analogue with the recurrence relation above.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] In this view, the factorial term *n*! is merely a counter-term to normalise the derivative operator acting on *x**n*.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The *Lambert series* of a sequence *a**n* is $\operatorname {LG} (a_{n};x)=\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }a_{n}{\frac {x^{n}}{1-x^{n}}}.$ Note that in a Lambert series the index n starts at 1, not at 0, as the first term would otherwise be undefined.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Formal Dirichlet series are often classified as generating functions, although they are not strictly formal power series.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] If *a**n* is a Dirichlet character then its Dirichlet series generating function is called a Dirichlet L-series.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] We also have a relation between the pair of coefficients in the Lambert series expansions above and their DGFs.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Namely, we can prove that: $[x^{n}]\operatorname {LG} (a_{n};x)=b_{n}$ if and only if $\operatorname {DG} (a_{n};s)\zeta (s)=\operatorname {DG} (b_{n};s),$ where *╬Č*(*s*) is the Riemann zeta function.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The idea of generating functions can be extended to sequences of other objects.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Thus, for example, polynomial sequences of binomial type are generated by: $e^{xf(t)}=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }{\frac {p_{n}(x)}{n!}}t^{n}$ where *p**n*(*x*) is a sequence of polynomials and *f*(*t*) is a function of a certain form.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Sheffer sequences are generated in a similar way.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] See the main article generalized Appell polynomials for more information.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] We see that for non-identically zero convolution families, this definition is equivalent to requiring that the sequence have an ordinary generating function of the first form given above.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Examples of convolution polynomial sequences include the *binomial power series*, ­Øōæ*t*(*z*) = 1 + *z*­Øōæ*t*(*z*)*t*, so-termed *tree polynomials*, the Bell numbers, *B*(*n*), the Laguerre polynomials, and the Stirling convolution polynomials.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Polynomials are a special case of ordinary generating functions, corresponding to finite sequences, or equivalently sequences that vanish after a certain point.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] These are important in that many finite sequences can usefully be interpreted as generating functions, such as the Poincar├® polynomial and others.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The left-hand side is the Maclaurin series expansion of the right-hand side.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Alternatively, the equality can be justified by multiplying the power series on the left by 1 ŌłÆ *x*, and checking that the result is the constant power series 1 (in other words, that all coefficients except the one of *x*0 are equal to 0).
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Moreover, there can be no other power series with this property.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The left-hand side therefore designates the multiplicative inverse of 1 ŌłÆ *x* in the ring of power series.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Expressions for the ordinary generating function of other sequences are easily derived from this one.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] One can also introduce regular gaps in the sequence by replacing x by some power of x, so for instance for the sequence 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, ...
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] so that we can form the analogous generating functions over the integral mth powers generalizing the result in the square case above.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The ordinary generating function of a sequence can be expressed as a rational function (the ratio of two finite-degree polynomials) if and only if the sequence is a linear recursive sequence with constant coefficients; this generalizes the examples above.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Conversely, every sequence generated by a fraction of polynomials satisfies a linear recurrence with constant coefficients; these coefficients are identical to the coefficients of the fraction denominator polynomial (so they can be directly read off).
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] This observation shows it is easy to solve for generating functions of sequences defined by a linear finite difference equation with constant coefficients, and then hence, for explicit closed-form formulas for the coefficients of these generating functions.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The prototypical example here is to derive Binet's formula for the Fibonacci numbers via generating function techniques.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] where the reciprocal roots, $\rho _{i}\in \mathbb {C}$ , are fixed scalars and where *p**i*(*n*) is a polynomial in n for all 1 Ōēż *i* Ōēż *Ōäō*.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] In general, Hadamard products of rational functions produce rational generating functions.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] This result is computed in many ways, including Cauchy's integral formula or contour integration, taking complex residues, or by direct manipulations of formal power series in two variables.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Multiplication of ordinary generating functions yields a discrete convolution (the Cauchy product) of the sequences.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] See also the section on convolutions in the applications section of this article below for further examples of problem solving with convolutions of generating functions and interpretations.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The differentiationŌĆōmultiplication operation of the second identity can be repeated k times to multiply the sequence by *n**k*, but that requires alternating between differentiation and multiplication.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Related operations of performing fractional integration on a sequence generating function are discussed here.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] In this section we give formulas for generating functions enumerating the sequence {*f**an* + *b*} given an ordinary generating function *F*(*z*), where *a* Ōēź 2, 0 Ōēż *b* < *a*, and *a* and *b* are integers (see the main article on transformations).
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] More generally, suppose that *a* Ōēź 3 and that *Žēa* = exp ŌüĀ2*ŽĆi*/*a*ŌüĀ denotes the ath primitive root of unity.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] where the coefficients *ci*(*z*) are in the field of rational functions, $\mathbb {C} (z)$ .
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Equivalently, $F(z)$ is holonomic if the vector space over $\mathbb {C} (z)$ spanned by the set of all of its derivatives is finite dimensional.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Since we can clear denominators if need be in the previous equation, we may assume that the functions, *ci*(*z*) are polynomials in z.
