[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] In other words, the properties that a sequence be *P-recursive* and have a holonomic generating function are equivalent.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Holonomic functions are closed under the Hadamard product operation ŌŖÖ on generating functions.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] and the non-convergent $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }n!\cdot z^{n}$ are all holonomic.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Examples of P-recursive sequences with holonomic generating functions include *f**n* Ōēö ŌüĀ1/*n* + 1ŌüĀ (2*n* *n*) and *f**n* Ōēö ŌüĀ2*n*/*n*2 + 1ŌüĀ, where sequences such as ${\sqrt {n}}$ and log *n* are *not* P-recursive due to the nature of singularities in their corresponding generating functions.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Similarly, functions with infinitely many singularities such as tan *z*, sec *z*, and ╬ō(*z*) are *not* holonomic functions.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Tools for processing and working with P-recursive sequences in *Mathematica* include the software packages provided for non-commercial use on the RISC Combinatorics Group algorithmic combinatorics software site.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Other packages listed on this particular RISC site are targeted at working with holonomic *generating functions* specifically.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] When the series converges absolutely, $G\left(a_{n};e^{-i\omega }\right)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}e^{-i\omega n}$ is the discrete-time Fourier transform of the sequence *a*0, *a*1, ....
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] In calculus, often the growth rate of the coefficients of a power series can be used to deduce a radius of convergence for the power series.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The reverse can also hold; often the radius of convergence for a generating function can be used to deduce the asymptotic growth of the underlying sequence.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Note that limit as n goes to infinity of the ratio of *a**n* to any of these expressions is guaranteed to be 1; not merely that *a**n* is proportional to them.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Often this approach can be iterated to generate several terms in an asymptotic series for *a**n*.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The asymptotic growth of the coefficients of this generating function can then be sought via the finding of A, B, ╬▒, ╬▓, and r to describe the generating function, as above.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Similar asymptotic analysis is possible for exponential generating functions; with an exponential generating function, it is ŌüĀ*a**n*/*n*!ŌüĀ that grows according to these asymptotic formulae.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Generally, if the generating function of one sequence minus the generating function of a second sequence has a radius of convergence that is larger than the radius of convergence of the individual generating functions then the two sequences have the same asymptotic growth.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] The generating function in several variables can be generalized to arrays with multiple indices.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] These non-polynomial double sum examples are called **multivariate generating functions**, or **super generating functions**.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] For two variables, these are often called **bivariate generating functions**.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] To do this, consider (1 + *x*)*n* itself as a sequence in n, and find the generating function in y that has these sequence values as coefficients.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Multivariate generating functions arise in practice when calculating the number of contingency tables of non-negative integers with specified row and column totals.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] Suppose the table has r rows and c columns; the row sums are *t*1, *t*2 ...
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p01] *tr* and the column sums are *s*1, *s*2 ...
