[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] A spanning tree is a subgraph of a graph which contains all of the original vertices and which contains enough edges to make this subgraph connected, but not so many edges that there is a cycle in the subgraph.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] We ask how many spanning trees *fn* of a fan of order n are possible for each *n* Ōēź 1.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] As an observation, we may approach the question by counting the number of ways to join adjacent sets of vertices.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] One often encounters generating functions specified by a functional equation, instead of an explicit specification.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] The Lagrange inversion theorem is a tool used to explicitly evaluate solutions to such equations.
