[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] The "Free Parameter" method is another method (called "snake oil" by H.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] Both methods discussed so far have n as limit in the summation.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] When n does not appear explicitly in the summation, we may consider n as a "free" parameter and treat *sn* as a coefficient of *F*(*z*) = ╬Ż *sn* *zn*, change the order of the summations on n and k, and try to compute the inner sum.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] It is instructive to use the same method again for the sum, but this time take m as the free parameter instead of n.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] If the "simpler" right-hand-side generating function, *B*(*z*), is a rational function of z, then the form of this sequence suggests that the sequence is eventually periodic modulo fixed particular cases of integer-valued *m* Ōēź 2.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] One useful method of obtaining congruences for sequences enumerated by special generating functions modulo any integers (i.e., not only prime powers *pk*) is given in the section on continued fraction representations of (even non-convergent) ordinary generating functions by J-fractions above.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] Generating functions also have other uses in proving congruences for their coefficients.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] We cite the next two specific examples deriving special case congruences for the Stirling numbers of the first kind and for the partition function *p*(*n*) which show the versatility of generating functions in tackling problems involving integer sequences.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] provides an overview of the congruences for these numbers derived strictly from properties of their generating function as in Section 4.6 of Wilf's stock reference *Generatingfunctionology*.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] and consequently shows that [*n* *k*] is even whenever *k* < ŌīŖ ŌüĀ*n*/2ŌüĀ Ōīŗ.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] In this example, we pull in some of the machinery of infinite products whose power series expansions generate the expansions of many special functions and enumerate partition functions.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] We show how to use generating functions and manipulations of congruences for formal power series to give a highly elementary proof of the first of these congruences listed above.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] There are a number of transformations of generating functions that provide other applications (see the main article).
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] A transformation of a sequence's *ordinary generating function* (OGF) provides a method of converting the generating function for one sequence into a generating function enumerating another.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] These transformations typically involve integral formulas involving a sequence OGF (see integral transformations) or weighted sums over the higher-order derivatives of these functions (see derivative transformations).
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] in the form of *S*(*z*) = *g*(*z*) *A*(*f*(*z*)) involving the original sequence generating function.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] For example, if the sums are $s_{n}:=\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }{\binom {n+k}{m+2k}}a_{k}\,$ then the generating function for the modified sum expressions is given by $S(z)={\frac {z^{m}}{(1-z)^{m+1}}}A\left({\frac {z}{(1-z)^{2}}}\right)$ (see also the binomial transform and the Stirling transform).
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] provided that these integrals converge for appropriate values of z.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] An initial listing of special mathematical series is found here.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] A number of useful and special sequence generating functions are found in Section 5.4 and 7.4 of *Concrete Mathematics* and in Section 2.5 of Wilf's *Generatingfunctionology*.
[src:functional-equations/generating-function-p02] Other special generating functions of note include the entries in the next table, which is by no means complete.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] In mathematics and computer science, a **recurrence relation** is an equation according to which the n th term of a sequence of numbers is equal to some combination of the previous terms.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Often, only k previous terms of the sequence appear in the equation, for a parameter k that is independent of n ; this number k is called the *order* of the relation.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] If the values of the first k numbers in the sequence have been given, the rest of the sequence can be calculated by repeatedly applying the equation.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] In *linear recurrences*, the nth term is equated to a linear function of the k previous terms.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A famous example is the recurrence for the Fibonacci numbers, $F_{n}=F_{n-1}+F_{n-2}$ where the order k is two and the linear function merely adds the two previous terms.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] This example is a linear recurrence with constant coefficients, because the coefficients of the linear function (1 and 1) are constants that do not depend on $n.$ For these recurrences, one can express the general term of the sequence as a closed-form expression of n .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] As well, linear recurrences with polynomial coefficients depending on n are also important, because many common elementary functions and special functions have a Taylor series whose coefficients satisfy such a recurrence relation (see holonomic function).
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Solving a recurrence relation means obtaining a closed-form solution: a non-recursive function of n .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The concept of a recurrence relation can be extended to multidimensional arrays, that is, indexed families that are indexed by tuples of natural numbers.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A *recurrence relation* is an equation that expresses each element of a sequence as a function of the preceding ones.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] is a function, where X is a set to which the elements of a sequence must belong.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] For any $u_{0}\in X$ , this defines a unique sequence with $u_{0}$ as its first element, called the *initial value*.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] It is easy to modify the definition for getting sequences starting from the term of index 1 or higher.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] This defines recurrence relation of *first order*.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] where $\varphi :\mathbb {N} \times X^{k}\to X$ is a function that involves k consecutive elements of the sequence.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] In this case, k initial values are needed for defining a sequence.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] for a given constant $r.$ The behavior of the sequence depends dramatically on $r,$ but is stable when the initial condition $x_{0}$ varies.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The recurrence of order two satisfied by the Fibonacci numbers is the canonical example of a homogeneous linear recurrence relation with constant coefficients (see below).
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A simple example of a multidimensional recurrence relation is given by the binomial coefficients ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ , which count the ways of selecting k elements out of a set of n elements.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Using this formula to compute the values of all binomial coefficients generates an infinite array called Pascal's triangle.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] with the initial value ${\textstyle {\binom {n}{0}}=1}$ (The division is not displayed as a fraction for emphasizing that it must be computed after the multiplication, for not introducing fractional numbers).
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The **difference operator** is an operator that maps sequences to sequences, and, more generally, functions to functions.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] It is thus a special case of finite difference.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A **difference equation** of order k is an equation that involves the k first differences of a sequence or a function, in the same way as a differential equation of order k relates the k first derivatives of a function.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The two above relations allow transforming a recurrence relation of order k into a difference equation of order k, and, conversely, a difference equation of order k into recurrence relation of order k.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Each transformation is the inverse of the other, and the sequences that are solution of the difference equation are exactly those that satisfies the recurrence relation.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] in the sense that the two equations are satisfied by the same sequences.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] See Rational difference equation, Linear constant-coefficient difference equation and Matrix difference equation for examples of using "difference equation" instead of "recurrence relation".
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Difference equations resemble differential equations, and this resemblance is often used to mimic methods for solving differentiable equations to apply to solving difference equations, and therefore recurrence relations.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Summation equations relate to difference equations as integral equations relate to differential equations.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] See time scale calculus for a unification of the theory of difference equations with that of differential equations.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Single-variable or one-dimensional recurrence relations are about sequences (i.e. functions defined on one-dimensional grids).
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Multi-variable or n-dimensional recurrence relations are about n -dimensional grids.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Functions defined on n -grids can also be studied with partial difference equations.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] If we apply the formula to $a_{n+1}=(1+hf_{nh})a_{n}+hg_{nh}$ and take the limit $h\to 0$ , we get the formula for first order linear differential equations with variable coefficients; the sum becomes an integral, and the product becomes the exponential function of an integral.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Many homogeneous linear recurrence relations may be solved by means of the generalized hypergeometric series.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Special cases of these lead to recurrence relations for the orthogonal polynomials, and many special functions.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Sequences which are the solutions of linear difference equations with polynomial coefficients are called P-recursive.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] For these specific recurrence equations algorithms are known which find polynomial, rational or hypergeometric solutions.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Furthermore, for the general non-homogeneous linear recurrence relation with constant coefficients, one can solve it based on variation of parameter.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A first order rational difference equation has the form $w_{t+1}={\tfrac {aw_{t}+b}{cw_{t}+d}}$ .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Such an equation can be solved by writing $w_{t}$ as a nonlinear transformation of another variable $x_{t}$ which itself evolves linearly.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Then standard methods can be used to solve the linear difference equation in $x_{t}$ .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The recurrence is stable, meaning that the iterates converge asymptotically to a fixed value, if and only if the eigenvalues (i.e., the roots of the characteristic equation), whether real or complex, are all less than unity in absolute value.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] with state vector x and transition matrix A , x converges asymptotically to the steady state vector $x^{*}$ if and only if all eigenvalues of the transition matrix A (whether real or complex) have an absolute value which is less than 1.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A nonlinear recurrence could have multiple fixed points, in which case some fixed points may be locally stable and others locally unstable; for continuous *f* two adjacent fixed points cannot both be locally stable.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A nonlinear recurrence relation could also have a cycle of period k for $k>1$ .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] where $x^{*}$ is any point on the cycle.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] In a chaotic recurrence relation, the variable x stays in a bounded region but never converges to a fixed point or an attracting cycle; any fixed points or cycles of the equation are unstable.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] See also logistic map, dyadic transformation, and tent map.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] When solving an ordinary differential equation numerically, one typically encounters a recurrence relation.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Systems of linear first order differential equations can be discretized exactly analytically using the methods shown in the discretization article.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Some of the best-known difference equations have their origins in the attempt to model population dynamics.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] For example, the Fibonacci numbers were once used as a model for the growth of a rabbit population.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The logistic map is used either directly to model population growth, or as a starting point for more detailed models of population dynamics.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] In this context, coupled difference equations are often used to model the interaction of two or more populations.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] with $N_{t}$ representing the hosts, and $P_{t}$ the parasites, at time t .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Integrodifference equations are a form of recurrence relation important to spatial ecology.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] These and other difference equations are particularly suited to modeling univoltine populations.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Recurrence relations are also of fundamental importance in analysis of algorithms.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] If an algorithm is designed so that it will break a problem into smaller subproblems (divide and conquer), its running time is described by a recurrence relation.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A simple example is the time an algorithm takes to find an element in an ordered vector with n elements, in the worst case.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A naive algorithm will search from left to right, one element at a time.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The worst possible scenario is when the required element is the last, so the number of comparisons is n .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] A better algorithm is called binary search.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] It will first check if the element is at the middle of the vector.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] If not, then it will check if the middle element is greater or lesser than the sought element.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] At this point, half of the vector can be discarded, and the algorithm can be run again on the other half.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] the time complexity of which will be $O(\log _{2}(n))$ .
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] In digital signal processing, recurrence relations can model feedback in a system, where outputs at one time become inputs for future time.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] They thus arise in infinite impulse response (IIR) digital filters.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] where $x_{t}$ is the input at time t , $y_{t}$ is the output at time t , and $\alpha$ controls how much of the delayed signal is fed back into the output.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] Recurrence relations, especially linear recurrence relations, are used extensively in both theoretical and empirical economics.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] In particular, in macroeconomics one might develop a model of various broad sectors of the economy (the financial sector, the goods sector, the labor market, etc.) in which some agents' actions depend on lagged variables.
[src:functional-equations/recurrence-relation] The model would then be solved for current values of key variables (interest rate, real GDP, etc.) in terms of past and current values of other variables.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The Riemann zeta function plays a pivotal role in analytic number theory and has applications in physics, probability theory, and applied statistics.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Leonhard Euler first introduced and studied the function over the reals in the first half of the eighteenth century.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Bernhard Riemann's 1859 article "On the Number of Primes Less Than a Given Magnitude" extended the Euler definition to a complex variable, proved its meromorphic continuation and functional equation, and established a relation between its zeros and the distribution of prime numbers.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] This paper also contained the Riemann hypothesis, a conjecture about the distribution of complex zeros of the Riemann zeta function that many mathematicians consider the most important unsolved problem in pure mathematics.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The values of the Riemann zeta function at even positive integers were computed by Euler.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The first of them, *╬Č*(2), provides a solution to the Basel problem.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In 1979, Roger Ap├®ry proved the irrationality of *╬Č*(3), and as a consequence, the number was named after him.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The values at negative integer points, also found by Euler, are rational numbers and play an important role in the theory of modular forms.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Many generalizations of the Riemann zeta function, such as Dirichlet series, Dirichlet *L*-functions and *L*-functions, are known.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The Riemann zeta function *╬Č*(*s*) is a function of a complex variable *s* = *Žā* + *it*, where *Žā* and *t* are real numbers.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The Riemann zeta function is defined for other complex values via analytic continuation of the function defined for *Žā* > 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Leonhard Euler considered the above series in 1740 for positive integer values of *s*, and later Chebyshev extended the definition to Re(*s*) > 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The above series is a prototypical Dirichlet series that converges absolutely to an analytic function for *s* such that *Žā* > 1 and diverges for all other values of *s*.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Riemann showed that the function defined by the series on the half-plane of convergence can be continued analytically to all complex values *s* ŌēĀ 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] For *s* = 1, the series is the harmonic series which diverges to +Ōł×, and $\lim _{s\to 1}(s-1)\zeta (s)=1.$ Thus the Riemann zeta function is a meromorphic function on the whole complex plane, which is holomorphic everywhere except for a simple pole at *s* = 1 with residue 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Both sides of the Euler product formula converge for Re(*s*) > 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The proof of Euler's identity uses only the formula for the geometric series and the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Since the harmonic series, obtained when *s* = 1, diverges, Euler's formula (which becomes ╬Ā*p* ŌüĀ*p*/*p* ŌłÆ 1ŌüĀ) implies that there are infinitely many primes.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Since the logarithm of *p*/(*p* ŌłÆ 1) is approximately 1/*p*, the formula can also be used to prove the stronger result that the sum of the reciprocals of the primes is infinite.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] On the other hand, combining that with the sieve of Eratosthenes shows that the density of the set of primes within the set of positive integers is zero.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The Euler product formula can be used to calculate the asymptotic probability that *s* randomly selected integers within a bound are set-wise coprime.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Intuitively, the probability that any single number is divisible by a prime (or any integer) *p* is 1/*p*.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Hence the probability that *s* numbers are all divisible by this prime is 1/*p**s*, and the probability that at least one of them is *not* is 1 ŌłÆ 1/*p**s*.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Now, for distinct primes, these divisibility events are mutually independent because the candidate divisors are coprime (a number is divisible by coprime divisors *n* and *m* if and only if it is divisible by *nm*, an event which occurs with probability 1/(*nm*)).
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] This zeta function satisfies the functional equation $\zeta (s)=2^{s}\pi ^{s-1}\ \sin \left({\frac {\pi s}{2}}\right)\ \Gamma (1-s)\ \zeta (1-s)\ ,$ where ╬ō(*s*) is the gamma function.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] This is an equality of meromorphic functions valid on the whole complex plane.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The equation relates values of the Riemann zeta function at the points *s* and 1 ŌłÆ *s*, in particular relating even positive integers with odd negative integers.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Owing to the zeros of the sine function, the functional equation implies that *╬Č*(*s*) has a simple zero at each even negative integer *s* = ŌłÆ2*n*, known as the **trivial zeros** of *╬Č*(*s*).
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] When *s* is an even positive integer, the product $\sin \left({\frac {\pi s}{2}}\right)\Gamma (1-s)$ on the right is non-zero because ╬ō(1 ŌłÆ *s*) has a simple pole, which cancels the simple zero of the sine factor.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] When *s* is 0, the zero of the sine factor is cancelled by the simple pole of *╬Č*(1).
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The functional equation was established by Riemann in his 1859 paper "On the Number of Primes Less Than a Given Magnitude" and used to construct the analytic continuation in the first place.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In the adelic formulation developed in Tate's thesis, the so-called Gamma factor $\pi ^{-s/2}\Gamma (s/2)$ is interpreted as the local zeta factor at the Archimedean place.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The functional equation shows that the Riemann zeta function has zeros at ŌłÆ2, ŌłÆ4, ....
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] They are trivial in the sense that their existence is relatively easy to prove, for example, from sin(*ŽĆs*/2) being 0 in the functional equation.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The non-trivial zeros have captured far more attention because their distribution not only is far less understood but, more importantly, their study yields important results concerning prime numbers and related objects in number theory.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] It is known that any non-trivial zero lies in the open strip {*s* Ōłł $\mathbb {C}$ | 0 < Re(*s*) < 1}, which is called the **critical strip**.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The Riemann hypothesis, considered one of the greatest unsolved problems in mathematics, asserts that all non-trivial zeros are on the critical line.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In 1989, Conrey proved that more than 40% of the non-trivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function are on the critical line.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] For the Riemann zeta function on the critical line, see *Z*-function.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Let *N*(*T*) be the number of zeros of *╬Č*(*s*) in the critical strip 0 < Re(*s*) < 1, whose imaginary parts are in the interval 0 < Im(*s*) < *T*.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Hardy proved that *╬Č*(ŌüĀ1/2ŌüĀ + *it*) has infinitely many real zeros.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Littlewood formulated two conjectures on the density and distance between the zeros of *╬Č*(1/2 + *it*) on intervals of large positive real numbers.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In the following, *N*(*T*) is the total number of real zeros and *N*0(*T*) the total number of zeros of odd order of the function *╬Č*(1/2 + *it*) lying in the interval (0, *T*].
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] These two conjectures opened up new directions in the investigation of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The location of the Riemann zeta function's zeros is of great importance in number theory.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The prime number theorem is equivalent to the fact that there are no zeros of the zeta function on the line Re(*s*) = 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] It is also known that zeros do not exist in certain regions slightly to the left of the line Re(*s*) = 1, known as zero-free regions.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] for any *╬Ą* > 0 and a number *c* > 0 depending on *╬Ą*.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Asymptotically, this is the largest known zero-free region for the zeta function.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Explicit zero-free regions are also known.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] for |*t*| Ōēź 2, which is the largest known zero-free region in the critical strip for 3Ōŗģ1012 < |*t*| < exp(64.1) Ōēł 7Ōŗģ1027 (for previous results see).
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] This is the largest known zero-free region for fixed |*t*| Ōēź exp(4.8Ōŗģ105).
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The strongest result of this kind one can hope for is the truth of the Riemann hypothesis, which would have many profound consequences in the theory of numbers.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] It is known that there are infinitely many zeros on the critical line.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The critical line theorem asserts that a positive proportion of the nontrivial zeros lies on the critical line.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In the critical strip, the zero with smallest non-negative imaginary part is 1/2 + 14.13472514...
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] implies that the zeros of the Riemann zeta function are symmetric about the real axis.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Combining this symmetry with the functional equation, furthermore, one sees that the non-trivial zeros are symmetric about the critical line Re(*s*) = 1/2.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] It is also known that no zeros lie on the line with real part 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] A large class of modified zeta functions exists that share the same non-trivial zeros as the Riemann zeta function, where modification means replacing the prime numbers in the Euler product by real numbers, which was shown in a result by Grosswald and Schnitzer.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] For odd positive integers, no such simple expression is known, although these values are thought to be related to the algebraic *K*-theory of the integers; see Special values of *L*-functions.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] For nonpositive integers, the series does not converge, but via analytic continuation one can show that $\zeta (-n)=-{\frac {B_{n+1}}{n+1}}$ for *n* Ōēź 0 (using the convention that *B*1 = 1/2).
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In particular, *╬Č* vanishes at the negative even integers because *B**m* = 0 for all odd *m* other than 1.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] These are the so-called "trivial zeros" of the zeta function.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Another particular value is $\zeta (-1)=-{\tfrac {1}{12}}$ This gives a pretext for assigning a finite value to the divergent series 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + Ōŗ», which has been used in certain contexts (Ramanujan summation) such as string theory.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Analogously, $\zeta (0)=-{\tfrac {1}{2}}$ can be viewed as assigning a finite result to the divergent series 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + Ōŗ».
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The value $\zeta {\bigl (}{\tfrac {1}{2}}{\bigr )}=-1.46035450880958681288\ldots$ is employed in calculating kinetic boundary layer problems of linear kinetic equations.
