[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] There are a number of similar relations involving various well-known multiplicative functions; these are given in the article on the Dirichlet series.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to the claim that this expression is valid when the real part of *s* is greater than 1/2.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The critical strip of the Riemann zeta function has the remarkable property of **universality**.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] This zeta function universality states, roughly, that vertical translates of $\zeta (s)$ can uniformly approximate any nonvanishing holomorphic function on suitable compact subsets of the strip $1/2<\operatorname {Re} (s)<1$ .
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Since holomorphic functions are very general, this property is quite remarkable.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The first proof of universality was provided by Sergei Mikhailovitch Voronin in 1975.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] More recent work has included effective versions of Voronin's theorem and extending it to Dirichlet *L*-functions.
