[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] A globally convergent series for the zeta function, valid for all complex numbers *s* except *s* = 1 + ŌüĀ2ŽĆ*i*/ln 2ŌüĀ*n* for some integer *n*, was conjectured by Konrad Knopp in 1926 and proven by Helmut Hasse in 1930 (cf.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The series appeared in an appendix to Hasse's paper, and was published for the second time by Jonathan Sondow in 1994.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Research by Iaroslav Blagouchine has found that a similar, equivalent series was published by Joseph Ser in 1926.
