[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Note that this representation of the zeta function is essentially an interpolation with nodes, where the nodes are points *s* = 2, 4, 6, ..., i.e. exactly those where the zeta values are precisely known, as Euler showed.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] An elegant and very short proof of this representation of the zeta function, based on Carlson's theorem, was presented by Philippe Flajolet in 2006.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The asymptotic behavior of the coefficients $A_{k}$ is rather curious: for growing k values, we observe regular oscillations with a nearly exponentially decreasing amplitude and slowly decreasing frequency (roughly as $k^{-2/3}$ ).
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] On the basis of this representation, in 2003 Luis B├Īez-Duarte provided a new criterion for the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Peter Borwein developed an algorithm that applies Chebyshev polynomials to the Dirichlet eta function to produce a very rapidly convergent series suitable for high precision numerical calculations.
