[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The function *g*(*x*) = *x*(1 + ŌīŖ*x*ŌłÆ1Ōīŗ) ŌłÆ 1 is iterated to find the coefficients appearing in Engel expansions.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The Brownian motion and Riemann zeta function are connected through the moment-generating functions of stochastic processes derived from the Brownian motion.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] A modern numerical algorithm is the OdlyzkoŌĆōSch├Čnhage algorithm.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The zeta function occurs in applied statistics including Zipf's law, ZipfŌĆōMandelbrot law, and Lotka's law.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Zeta function regularization is used as one possible means of regularization of divergent series and divergent integrals in quantum field theory.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In one notable example, the Riemann zeta function shows up explicitly in one method of calculating the Casimir effect.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The zeta function is also useful for the analysis of dynamical systems.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] In the theory of musical tunings, the zeta function can be used to find equal divisions of the octave (EDOs) that closely approximate the intervals of the harmonic series.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] peaks near integers that correspond to such EDOs.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] Examples include popular choices such as 12, 19, and 53.
[src:functional-equations/riemann-zeta-function] The zeta function evaluated at equidistant positive integers appears in infinite series representations of a number of constants.
